        <body>
            <div type="emblem" n="e50"><!-- Change the value of n to "e" followed by the number of the emblem. Use two digits for all numbers. -->
                <pb n="155"/><!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                
                
                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Embleme</orig> 50. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>The Dragon kills the woman, and <choice><orig>shee</orig> him, and are both bloody
                        <lb/>all over.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 50.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l><orig>Fitt</orig> for the Dragon <choice><orig>digge</orig><reg>dig</reg></choice> a cavous<!-- ? --> place,</l>
                        <l>And therewith <choice><orig>joyne</orig> the woman face to face:</l>
                        <l>Whilst <choice><orig>hee</orig> the <choice><orig>joyes</orig><reg>joys</reg></choice> of <choice><orig>wedlocke</orig><reg>wedlock</reg></choice> reaps, <choice><orig>shee</orig> <choice><orig>dyes</orig>,</l>
                        <l>With <choice><orig>whome</orig> entomb him, that <choice><orig>hee</orig> may not rise;</l>
                        <l>This is <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>killd</orig>, and <choice><orig>ting'd</orig><reg>tinged</reg></choice> with blood all <choice><orig>o're</orig><reg>over</reg></choice>:</l>
                        <l>Take but this course, and you need <choice><orig>aske</orig> <choice><orig>noe</orig> more</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="156"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 50.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>The mansion of Dragons is in caverns of the earth, but the residence<milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/>of men above the earth in the <choice><orig>iḿediate</orig> <choice><orig>aire</orig>; which two Elements
                        <lb/>are contrary, and appointed by the Philosophers to be <choice><orig>joynd</orig> together,
                        <lb/>that one may act upon the other: But by the woman others <choice><orig>meane</orig>, as
                        <lb/>Basill in Key 2d. <choice><orig>sayth</orig>: For it is not convenient or <choice><orig>coḿodious</orig> for an<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Eagle to place her nest upon the Alps, because her chickens would <choice><orig>dye</orig>
                        <lb/>through the <choice><orig>coldnesse</orig> of the Snow at the top of the mountains: But
                        <lb/>if you add to the Eagle a cold Dragon, which <choice><orig>hath</orig> had his habitation
                        <lb/>a long time in the rocks, and crept out of the caves of the earth,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and put them both into an <choice><orig>infernall</orig> sell, then will Pluto blow a<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>blast, and draw a volatile fiery spirit out of the cold dragon, which
                        <lb/>with its great heat will <choice><orig>burne</orig> the Eagles feathers, and excite such a
                        <lb/><orig>sudorificke</orig> bath, as to melt the Snow at the top of the mountains,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and <choice><orig>turne</orig> it into water; from which a minerable bath may be well<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>præpared</orig>, contributing fortune and health to the King. Admirable in
                        <lb break="no"/>deed it is, that a cold dragon should <choice><orig>yeild</orig> a fiery Spirit; yet experience<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>declares it to be true in burned serpents, which <choice><orig>doe</orig> send forth a venomous<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>flame <choice><orig>poysoning</orig> the standers by: Nor in <choice><orig>vayne</orig><reg>vain</reg></choice> are the keepers of the <choice><orig>Chy
                        <lb break="no"/>micall</orig> treasures called flammivomous dragons, as the keepers of the golden
                        <lb/>fleece, the Hesperian gardens, Cadmus, and the like. But this dragon lives
                        <lb/>in <choice><orig>streight</orig><reg>straight</reg></choice> places of subterranean rocks, which you must there take, and
                        <lb/><orig>joyne</orig> to the Eagle or woman, to her, in the grave, to the other, if you<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>had rather, in the nest: For the nature of a dragon is sometimes to <choice><orig>lye</orig> in
                        <lb/><choice><orig>waite</orig><reg>wait</reg></choice> for the Eagles eggs, and wage <choice><orig>mortall</orig><reg>mortal</reg></choice> <choice><orig>warre</orig> with the Eagle: Some
                        <lb/>there are of the <choice><orig>Græcian</orig><reg>Grecian</reg></choice> writers who <choice><orig>affirme</orig> that a dragon in times past<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>fell in love with a <choice><orig>mayd</orig><reg>maid</reg></choice> and lay with her. What wonder therefore, if
                        <lb/>the Philosophers would have their dragon <choice><orig>shutt</orig> up in a <choice><orig>caverne</orig><reg>cavern</reg></choice> with a<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>woman? Greverus <choice><orig>joynes</orig> red and <choice><orig>blacke</orig> dragons together in the deep<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><choice><orig>gulfe</orig><reg>gulf</reg></choice> of the <choice><orig>mountaine</orig>, and <choice><orig>burnes</orig> them with fire, and the <choice><orig>blacke</orig> pe
                        <lb break="no"/>rishing, <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>sayth</orig> that the keeper of the <choice><orig>mountaine</orig> <choice><orig>searcheth</orig><reg>searchs</reg></choice> for them
                        <lb/>every where, and brings them to the <choice><orig>mountaine</orig>. Merlin in his vision (if it
                        <lb/>be not suppositious) makes mention of a white and red dragon; These
                        <lb/>Dragons, whatsoever they be, whether one be a woman, or a female<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>dragon, <choice><orig>doe</orig> act one with the other, till they both <choice><orig>dye</orig>, and <choice><orig>emitt</orig><reg>emit</reg></choice> blood
                        <lb/>from their wounds, wherewith they are <choice><orig>embrued</orig><reg>imbrued</reg></choice>. But here the element
                        <lb/>of earth and fire is understood by the dragon, and by the woman the
                        <lb/>element of <choice><orig>aire</orig> and water; whereupon <choice><orig>sayth</orig> Clangor buccinæ: The Dragon
                        <lb/>is the matter remaining in the <choice><orig>bottome</orig> after the water be <choice><orig>distilld</orig><reg>distilled</reg></choice> from
                        <lb/>it: And according to Hermes: The water of <choice><orig>aire</orig> being between heaven and
                        <lb/>earth is the life of every thing, for that water dissolves a body into a<pc>-</pc>
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="157"/><fw>Discourse 50.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb/>spirit, and <choice><orig>vivifyes</orig><reg>vivifies</reg></choice> a dead thing, and makes matrimony between man and wo
                        <lb break="no"/>man: For it <choice><orig>conferrs</orig><reg>confers</reg></choice> the whole <choice><orig>benefitt</orig><reg>benefit</reg></choice> of the art: Of the earth <choice><orig>allso</orig> <choice><orig>hee</orig> thus
                        <lb/>speaks. And moreover understand, that the particular earth, which <choice><orig>wee</orig> tread
                        <lb/>upon, is not the true element, <choice><orig>yea</orig> is elemented with its true fifth element: Nor
                        <lb/><orig>doth</orig> the fifth <choice><orig>elementall</orig> substance recede from its elemented body, of which
                        <lb/>the earth is formed. And a little after. But the Virgin and true element,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>which fire cannot <choice><orig>burne</orig>, is in the center of the earth: This is the dragon,
                        <lb/>whereof <choice><orig>wee</orig> <choice><orig>speake</orig>, insinuating <choice><orig>itselfe</orig> even into the center of the earth,
                        <lb/>where the heat being great, it conceives within <choice><orig>itselfe</orig> a flaming heat, where
                        <lb break="no"/>with it <choice><orig>burnes</orig> the woman or eagle. The woman or eagle is indeed an airy<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>water, which some call the white or <choice><orig>cælestiall</orig> eagle, and will have it made
                        <lb/>of <choice><orig>coḿon</orig> Mercury, or sublimed Salts, following therein the sense of some <choice><orig>cer
                        <lb break="no"/>taine</orig> men blind in this art, <choice><orig>faigning</orig><reg>feigning</reg></choice> themselves to be quicksighted; But<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>sayth</orig> Count Bernhard in his Epistle, I tell you <choice><orig>truely</orig>, that <choice><orig>noe</orig> water dissolves
                        <lb/>a <choice><orig>metallicke</orig> species by <choice><orig>naturall</orig> reduction, except that which continues with<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>it in matter and <choice><orig>forme</orig>, and which the <choice><orig>metalls</orig> themselves can <choice><orig>recongeale</orig><reg>recongeal</reg></choice>:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>And a little after: Nor <choice><orig>doth</orig> that water <choice><orig>appertaine</orig> to <choice><orig>bodyes</orig> in solutions, which
                        <lb/>remains not with them in congelations: And a little after: I tell you <choice><orig>truely</orig>,
                        <lb/>that the <choice><orig>oyle</orig> which naturally incerates and <choice><orig>joyns</orig> natures together, and natu
                        <lb break="no"/>rally <choice><orig>introduceth</orig><reg>introduces</reg></choice> a Medicine for the tinging of other <choice><orig>bodyes</orig>, is not compounded
                        <lb/>of any other extraneous thing, but <choice><orig>onely</orig> of the <choice><orig>bowells</orig> of the body which is
                        <lb/>to be dissolved: This therefore being apprehended, the eagle and woman, as
                        <lb/><orig>allso</orig> the Dragon with the secrets of <choice><orig>allmost</orig> the whole art are understood,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>which perhaps <choice><orig>wee</orig> have thus <choice><orig>farre</orig> too openly explained and declared to
                        <lb/>the <choice><orig>Sonns</orig> of learning, that God may hereby be <choice><orig>glorifyed</orig><reg>glorified</reg></choice><pc>. . . . .</pc>
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
            </div>
